StoreLens Frontend Blueprint for AI Copilot
1. Project Identity & Context
You are an expert Frontend Developer building StoreLens - a real-time retail analytics dashboard.

Goal: Visualize customer behavior data processed by Edge AI.

Key Features: Real-time KPIs, Heatmaps, Dwell-time charts, Zone configuration.

Design System: Modern, Dark-themed (optional), Glassmorphism, Responsive.

2. Technical Stack (Strict Adherence)
Framework: React 18+ (Vite)

Language: TypeScript

Styling: Tailwind CSS

Icons: Lucide React

Charts: Recharts

State Management: Redux Toolkit (Thunks for Async)

Animations: Framer Motion

API Client: Axios

3. Database Schema Knowledge (Source of Truth)
When generating mock data or types, strictly follow these schemas from the backend:

A. StoreSummary (storesSummary.model.js)
storeId: ObjectId

total_people_count: Number

total_revenue: Number

avg_dwell_time: Number

conversion_rate: Number (total_invoices / total_people_count)

B. ZoneStats (zonesSummary.model.js)
zone_id: ObjectId

people_count: Number

performance.conversion_rate: Number

performance.avg_dwell_time: Number

performance.total_stop_events: Number

trend: "up" | "down" | "steady"

C. Heatmap (heatmap.model.js)
camera_id: ObjectId

data_points: Array of { x: number, y: number, intensity: number }

4. UI/UX "Vibe" Guidelines
Containers: Use bg-white/10 backdrop-blur-md border border-white/20 for a glassmorphism look.

Colors:

Primary: Indigo/Violet for tech vibe.

Success: Emerald for positive trends.

Danger: Rose for drops in traffic.

Charts: Use ResponsiveContainer from Recharts. Keep colors consistent (e.g., Traffic is always Blue, Revenue is always Green).

5. Development Instructions for Copilot
Component Creation Rule:
Always use Functional Components with TypeScript Interfaces.

Keep logic (hooks) separate from presentation where possible.

Use clsx or tailwind-merge for dynamic classes.

Mocking Logic:
When asked to /mock, create realistic data that mimics a real store (e.g., peak traffic at 18:00, higher dwell time in "Clothing" zone compared to "Entrance").

State Management:
Use useSelector and useDispatch from react-redux.

Slices should be organized by feature: dashboardSlice, zoneSlice, authSlice.

6. Project Structure Mapping
Plaintext
src/
 ├── assets/          # Static assets (logo, images)
 ├── components/      # Atomic UI components (Buttons, Cards, Modals)
 ├── features/        # Business logic & Page-level components
 │    ├── Dashboard/  # KPI cards, Global charts
 │    ├── Heatmap/    # Canvas-based density mapping
 │    └── Analytics/  # Dwell time & Zone comparison
 ├── redux/           # Store config & Slices
 ├── services/        # Axios instance & API calls
 ├── styles/          # Tailwind & Global CSS
 └── utils/           # Formatters (currency, time, stop_watch)